Looking at the structure:
- `Algebra.algebraMap (max (RCLike.re (g x)) 0)` will map the maximum of the real part (or 0) back into the complex field.
- `Algebra.algebraMap (max (-RCLike.re (g x)) 0)` will map the maximum of the negative real part (or 0) back.
- Similarly for the imaginary parts.

The key insight is that `max (RCLike.re (g x)) 0` is just `RCLike.re (g x)` if it's non-negative, or 0 if it's negative. But in complex numbers, the real part can be negative. So this is a way to take the "positive" part of the real component.

Similarly, `max (-RCLike.re (g x)) 0` is ` -RCLike.re (g x)` if it's non-negative (i.e., `RCLike.re (g x)` is non-positive), or 0 if `RCLike.re (g x)` is positive.

So the first two terms `Algebra.algebraMap (max (RCLike.re (g x)) 0) - Algebra.algebraMap (max (-RCLike.re (g x)) 0)` will give us:
- If `RCLike.re (g x) ≥ 0`: `RCLike.re (g x) - 0 = RCLike.re (g x)`
- If `RCLike.re (g x) < 0`: `0 - (-RCLike.re (g x)) = RCLike.re (g x)`

So the first two terms always sum to `RCLike.re (g x)`.

