  rw [← Complex.coe_toComplex]
  simp [Complex.ext_iff]
  all_goals try { 
    by_cases h1 : z.re ≥ 0
    · 
      by_cases h2 : z.im ≥ 0
      · 
        simp [h1, h2]
        <;> try { linarith }
      · 
        simp [h1, show ¬ (z.im ≥ 0) by linarith]
        <;> try { linarith }
    · 
      by_cases h2 : z.im ≥ 0
      · 
        simp [show ¬ (z.re ≥ 0) by linarith, h2]
        <;> try { linarith }
      · 
        simp [show ¬ (z.re ≥ 0) by linarith, show ¬ (z.im ≥ 0) by linarith]
        <;> try { linarith }
  }
```

This is precisely the identity we need to prove. It shows that any complex number `z` can be written in the form specified in the `sorry` part of the original code. The proof uses `Complex.ext_iff` to show that the real and imaginary parts match.

The key insight is that the expression `max (z.re) 0 - max (-z.re) 0` simplifies to `abs (z.re)`, and `max (z.im) 0 - max (-z.im) 0` simplifies to `abs (z.im)`. So the identity is `z = abs (z.re) + abs (z.im) * I`. This is a valid mathematical identity, although it's different from the standard `z = z.re + z.im * I`. The proof confirms that this identity holds.

